previous_headings: Running the SpeciesPoolR Workflow
title: How to use the SpeciesPoolR package
text: run_workflow function creates pipeline : Reads data specified file path. Filters data using provided filter expression. Cleans species names match GBIF taxonomic backbone. Counts species presences within specified geographic area (case, Aarhus). Generates buffer around species presences within specified distance, using template raster. Prepares land-use data generating long-format table matches raster cell corresponding habitat types. Predicts habitat suitability species across different land-use types using ModelAndPredictFunc, models habitat preferences provides continuous predictions. Generates habitat suitability thresholds species based predicted suitability scores, using create_thresholds function define 90th, 95th, 99th percentile thresholds. Builds lookup table determine land-use types species can inhabit based thresholds. Generates final species presences filtering buffered presences according lookup table long land-use table, ensuring species’ potential distribution consistent habitat preferences. Generates phylogenetic tree species species list, using generate_tree function. Generates visual representation workflow plot = TRUE. can monitor progress workflow visualize dependencies steps using targets::tar_visnetwork(). result similar running steps manually added benefits parallel execution reproducibility. automated approach allows streamline analysis ensures steps consistently applied data. also makes easier rerun workflow different parameters datasets.

title: Read in Data from a CSV or XLSX File — get_data

title: Read in Data from a CSV or XLSX File — get_data
text: data.frame containing data read file, optionally filtered.

title: Read in Data from a CSV or XLSX File — get_data
code: if (FALSE) { # \dontrun{ # Read in data without filtering f <- system.file("ex/Species_List.csv", package="SpeciesPoolR") data <- get_data(f)  # Read in data and filter for Plantae kingdom and certain taxon ranges filtered_data <- get_data(   file = f,   filter = quote(    Kingdom == "Plantae" &    Class == "Magnoliopsida"   ) ) } # }

what: Filter Species Presences by Habitat Suitability — make_final_presences
title: Filter Species Presences by Habitat Suitability — make_final_presences
text: function takes long-format land-use table, buffer data frame species presences, lookup table determine species can thrive habitats. filters species presences include cells within species' buffer zones suitable habitats according lookup table.

title: Filter Species Presences by Habitat Suitability — make_final_presences
Filter Species Presences by Habitat Suitability — make_final_presences
text: Long_LU_table long-format data frame containing land-use suitability data, generated generate_long_landuse_table. Long_Buffer_gbif data frame containing buffer zones species presences, typically generated earlier workflow. LookUpTable data frame containing lookup table maps species suitable habitats.

title: Filter Species Presences by Habitat Suitability — make_final_presences
text: data table filtered species presences. returned data table includes cell identifier corresponding species can thrive cell based habitat suitability.

title: Filter Species Presences by Habitat Suitability — make_final_presences
code: # Assuming you have the following objects from previous steps: # Long_LU_table - The long-format land-use suitability table # Long_Buffer_gbif - The buffer data frame of species presences # LookUpTable - The lookup table mapping species to suitable habitats  final_presences <- make_final_presences(Long_LU_table, Long_Buffer_gbif, LookUpTable) #> Error in eval(expr, envir, enclos): object 'Long_Buffer_gbif' not found

title: Run the SpeciesPoolR Workflow — run_workflow
text: function sets runs targets workflow using functions provided SpeciesPoolR package. workflow includes steps cleaning species data, counting species presences, filtering data, generating buffers spatial analysis.

title: Run the SpeciesPoolR Workflow — run_workflow
code: run_workflow(   workers = 2,   error = "null",   file_path,   rastertemp,   rasterLU,   LanduseSuitability,   dist = 500,   filter = NULL,   country = NULL,   shapefile = NULL,   plot = TRUE )

title: Run the SpeciesPoolR Workflow — run_workflow
text: workers Number parallel workers use crew controller. Default 2. error Handling errors outdated targets. Default "null". file_path Path Excel csv file containing data. rastertemp file path raster file used template rasterizing buffers. rasterLU file path raster file landuses exist area modeled. LanduseSuitability string representing file path raster file containing land-use binary suitability data. dist numeric value specifying buffer distance meters. Default 500 meters. filter optional expression used filter resulting data.frame. expression written using dplyr::filter(). default NULL, meaning filtering applied. country two-letter country code define area interest counting species presences. Default NULL. shapefile Path shapefile defining area interest counting species presences. Default NULL. plot TRUE (default) run targets::tar_visnetwork() plot workflow

title: Run the SpeciesPoolR Workflow — run_workflow
text: Executes targets pipeline.

title: Write Cloud Optimized Geotiff (COG) — write_cog
Write Cloud Optimized Geotiff (COG) — write_cog
text: SpatRaster SpatRaster object (class SpatRaster) representing raster data saved COG. Name desired name COG file, including ".tif" extension.

title: Write Cloud Optimized Geotiff (COG) — write_cog
text: Cloud Optimized Geotiff saved specified location.

title: Write Cloud Optimized Geotiff (COG) — write_cog
code: # Load required libraries if not already loaded # library(terra)  # Create a sample SpatRaster r <- terra::rast(nrows = 5, ncols = 5, vals = 1:25)  # Save the SpatRaster as a COG write_cog(SpatRaster = r, Name = "test.tif")  # Clean up later file.remove("test.tif") #> [1] TRUE file.remove("test.tfw") #> [1] TRUE
